# Authentication via Clerk

Use `@clerk/nextjs` for all authentication. Never roll custom auth.

## Enforcing Data Ownership

Every server-side data access (Server Components, Server Actions, API routes) must scope queries to the authenticated user. Never trust user-supplied IDs alone — always verify ownership.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — trusts client-supplied deckId without ownership check
const deck = await db.select().from(decks).where(eq(decks.id, deckId));

// ✅ GOOD — scopes query to the authenticated user
import { auth } from "@clerk/nextjs/server";

const { userId } = await auth();
if (!userId) throw new Error("Unauthorized");

const deck = await db
  .select()
  .from(decks)
  .where(and(eq(decks.id, deckId), eq(decks.userId, userId)));
```

## Rules

- Call `auth()` from `@clerk/nextjs/server` at the start of every server-side data operation.
- Reject immediately if `userId` is null.
- Include `eq(table.userId, userId)` in every `select`, `update`, and `delete` query.
- On `insert`, always set `userId` from the auth context — never from client input.
- For child records (e.g., `cards` → `decks`), join or subquery to confirm the parent belongs to the user before reading or mutating.
